title: Has a typo ever had disastrous consequences? - Quora

response.answer_text: Well, I wouldn’t say “disastrous,” but one of my students made a typo (or perhaps he had a brain freeze) on an essay about crime reporting. It happens that rapes are underreported due to many factors - embarrassment, not wanting to go through invasive medical testing, embarrassing interviews, the blame the victim mentality, etc. So, the student wrote that “rape is one of the most underrated crimes.” Of course I red-underlined that and put a big X and he lost some credit, but I knew it was a typo and I doubt he even noticed his error and the potential for an unfortunate different interpretation. Consequences, yes, but - certainly not disastrous. In another case, disastrous for the student but more than a typo. I read a student paper that seemed familiar, in some odd way. The student mixed up some words, used some expressions and phrases oddly, and made some errors that just seemed like deja vu. I often saved student papers that were particularly excellent or horrible, so I went to the relevant file drawer, pulled out the stack of papers on that particular topic, and guess what - there was the two- or three-year-old paper (written by a former student) that was the source of the familiar deja-vu memories. There were the SAME mixed up words, and the SAME odd phrasing. AND, in a few cases where I had circled errors and jotted notes about corrections, the current (second) paper was corrected (at least once, corrected incorrectly). So…..I showed both papers to my department chair and some other faculty members, all of whom agreed with me that it was an obvious case of plagiarism. I called the student into my office, showed him both papers, and he absolutely denied any copying or plagiarism. How COULD I POSSIBLY THINK THAT HE WOULD HAVE DONE SUCH A THING? He insisted that HE, and only HE, had written the paper, and said that he wrote it on his laptop while on a team bus to an away game. He said that the team captain and even his coach had seen him writing the paper. I filed formal plagiarism charges (as much because of his obvious lies and his act that somehow I was being unfair as because of the copying). With a little research I determined that he and the author of the original paper were on the same team a few years ago. In a subsequent conversation the current student said that the former teammate had lent him his disc with the paper on it, to help give him some ideas about the paper. (That was against college policy, but to read one or more “sample papers” to get an idea of “what the prof wants” didn’t seem unreasonable to me.) He brought the team captain and the coach into the plagiarism hearing to make statements on his behalf, thus directly involving them in his lies. Where he could have settled for a zero on the paper, and probably a D in the class, he instead was found guilty of plagiarism, assigned a mandatory F in the class, AND, because of entangling the two others in his case, he was suspended from the college for the next semester or year. And THOSE are disastrous consequences, though it was a lot more than a “typo”.

Not exactly a typo but I think worthy of inclusion Importance of Original Knowledge Principle #1: Don't trust retellers, get hold of the original sources. A new monk arrives at the monastery. He is assigned to help the other monks in copying the old texts by hand. He notices, however, that they are copying copies, and not the original books. So, the new monk goes to the head monk to ask him about this. He points out that if there was an error in the first copy, that error would be continued in all of the other copies. The head monk says, "We have been copying from the copies for centuries, but you make a good point, my son." So, he goes down into the cellar with one of the copies to check it against the original. Hours later, nobody has seen him. So, one of the monks goes downstairs to look for him. He hears sobbing coming from the back of the cellar and finds the old monk leaning over one of the original books crying. He asks what's wrong. "The word is celebrate not celibate," says the old monk with tears in his eyes. Oh, no! Didactic Jokes Just have to wonder what the world would be like if they got it right Edited to add another “did not happen” typo but might have had bad outcome if it had. Brought to you from a friend's email A man received the following sms from his neighbour "I am sorry Bob I've been riddled with guilt and have to make a confession I have been helping myself to your wife day and night when you're not around In fact I have probably been getting more than you I do not get it at home but that's no excuse I can no longer live with the guilt and I hope you will accept my sincerest apology with my promise that it won't ever happen again" On reading the sms the man, anguished and betrayed grabbed his gun went directly into his bedroom and shot his wife A few moments later a second text came in "Bloody spell check Sorry Bob the second sentence should say wifi not wife" Hope never happens for real

Once upon a time, the US did nuclear tests. That’s fairly common knowledge. What is less commonly known is that reports of those nuclear tests, which were released after a certain period of time, caused an international incident. According to the reports, the US had conducted nuclear tests in the Sudan. Obviously, this caused an enormous amount of uproar, both in the US and in the international community. It raised the issue of the status of the US as a superpower and the ensuing potential for massive abuses in power and violations of sovereignty. Extensive hearings were conducted by Congress in order to get to the bottom of the situation. Ultimately, it turned out that the secretary who had typed up the report had made a mistake. The US had never detonated nukes in tests in the Sudan; they did, however, blow up a sedan. And that’s how a typo came close to causing a war. EDIT: I got the story from my professor in US Foreign Policy, Howard Tamashiro, from a lecture on the nature of problems in politics, in September, 2017. I’m not completely sure about further reading for the Sudan/sedan issue, specifically, but the books for the class were very interesting. The Cold War, Westad A decent overview of how the events of the twentieth century led into the Cold War, followed by a broad and inclusive analysis of the war itself. I would caution that he does not specialize in the history of the world wars and his analyses of them, as well as, in some cases, his facts, are somewhat flawed. A Noble Cause? by De Groot A very readable book on the Vietnam War. He draws on the pre-existing collection of Vietnam studies to excellent effect, providing a clear and well-rounded picture of the conflict. We Meant Well, Van Buren At once funny and depressing, this is a diplomat’s view of being in the field for the work of reconstructing Iraq. A comedy of errors of vast proportions with government incompetence in the starring role. In the Shadows of the American Century, McCoy A book on the rise and decline of American power and influence. Some of his conclusions are rather troubling, but his logic is, for the most part, sound. America’s War for the Greater Middle East, Bacevich Very well-written, and even more depressing than Van Buren.

One famous example that has become a case study for health informatics (specifically computer control of medical machinery) and computer science/software engineering is the Therac-25 - Wikipedia. I originally learned about this as a computer science major in my computer ethics class. This was an x-ray machine used for radiation therapy not for taking x-ray images. It had a direct electron beam mode where a narrow low power beam was aimed at specific places on the patient as well as a x-ray therapy mode where a much more powerful beam (100 times more current) was aimed at a target inside the machine which caused the beam to spread out over a much larger area as well as absorbing much of the power of the beam. There were bugs in the software that controlled the machine (a kind of typo already) that allowed the high power beam to project directly on to the patient (instead of the target) when the operator (radiology tech) typed a particular sequence of keys (first X to incorrectly to select the x-ray therapy mode (a typo), then cursor up to go back to the previous field to correct it, then E to correctly select electron therapy mode) all within 8 seconds and then also overriding a generic MALFUNCTION message by typing P to override the error and continue. This particular combination of events did not happen very often so it took quite a while to track down the problem and resolve it. The problem caused six different patients to receive about 1000 times as much radiation as was intended and over a much narrower part of their bodies than intended. All the patients suffered radiation burns and radiation poisoning and three of the six died as a result. So, I’d say a specific typo that killed 3 people qualifies as a pretty disastrous consequence, at least in my book.

Here’s my answer. Not sure if it was technically a typo but I’ll share anyway. I was 16 years old. Working two jobs. One of my jobs was for a startup car leasing company. I was hired to help distribute marketing material. My task: Send a pdf to all the email addresses in a database. There were 6000 email addresses. So I knew if you separated each email address by a comma you could send an email to multiple addresses at the same time using Microsoft outlook. I also knew I could export the email address column from the database as comma separated values. My idea is obvious from there is it not? So after a bit of jiggery pokery I managed to get a list of 6000 email addresses each separated by a comma and a space. All I had to do was copy and paste the addresses into the BCC box, add the content, click send and feel victorious. Unfortunately though, the mail server the company used wasn’t working with outlook that day. So I logged onto their website and proceeded to repeat the steps using thier own online mail client, which was working. I copied the 6000 email addresses into the BCC box, added the content, and hit send. I felt victorious. That lasted until the following day. I got a call at about tea time. It was the boss. He had been receiving phone calls all day from various companies that might have been found in the database I was given. It turns out that each email address not only got the email I sent, but they each got it 6000 times. That’s 36,000,000 emails with a click of button. Each caller explained how in trying to download so many emails, thier server would slow down to a crawl (this was 13ish years ago) and there was nothing thay could do about it. So 6000 companies pretty much took the day off. They went on the create an alliance and sue the guy I worked for, for millions I believe. Unfortunately he passed away shortly after and I never did find out what happened.

On June 15, 1992, Vice President Dan Quayle attended a spelling bee at Luis Muñoz Rivera Elementary School. There he calls 12-year-old William Figueroa to the blackboard to spell the word “potato.” With chalk in hand, the boy spells “potato” correctly, then erases the board. A gentleman asks the boy to spell it again, and he does; but, this time the Vice President adds: That’s fine phonetically, but you’re missing just a little bit. The boy is confused at first, but he eventually adds an “e” to the end of the word making it “potatoe.” When he finishes he receives a round of applause then sits down. Because of this gaffe, Quayle spent the coming months being made fun of by media personalities, fellow politicians, and people who attended the conventions where he spoke. Quayle tried defending himself by saying the flashcard the school gave him spelled “potato” as “potatoe”; but, it didn’t matter. To most people, this incident was the last straw on the long lists of incidents by Quayle. A few months later on November 3, 1992, Bill Clinton and Al Gore replaced George H.W. Bush and Dan Quayle as President and Vice-President of The United States. Though the “potato” gaffe wasn’t the main reason why Bush and Quayle didn't get reelected, it sure didn’t help.

Ouch, it hurts to read some of the comments made by Quora users. Let me tell you a different situation. NOTE: I am by no means trying to be racist. I try not to make differences between races, genders, etc. Penguin Books Australia in 2010 published a book, actually a cookbook. But they had to destroy 7000 copies costing them over $20,000. Although people mentioned situations costing companies in millions of dollars of damage, I still think it’s worth mentioning, as no one already did. In that cookbook, there was a recipe for tagliatelle with sardines and prosciutto.  That’s what it should look like at the end, if you did it following the right recipe. But this book provided a wrong one, actually the one that went really wrong. Head of publishing, Robert Sessions told that he felt ashamed after they found out that there was a typo in their book that caused the damage. He also stated that he sees no reason why anyone would feel offended. All right, back to the main part. One of the ingredients this book required was “salt and freshly ground black people”. No, you did not misread it. What they actually wanted to list as an ingredient is freshly ground black pepper. Later on, they decided to post a statement on their website offering sincere apologies and they offered to replace the copies of this book for the right ones. I can’t imagine what I would feel like to hear that my publishing company had published copies of that book. PS: Thank you Sarah Madden and Shounak Hinge for helping me to get rid of typos in my answer. Although these typos didn’t have any disastrous consequences, I still think it’s worth getting rid of all of them!

response.answer_text: The Trump Presidency (disastrous or glorious according to your politics). Remember the Russian hacking of the American election? It still lingers with us, as investigations into Trump and collusion with foreign governments goes on and on and on (and on). Yet what the “hacking” was is almost never discussed or mentioned. It was all on account of a mere typo. Russia didn’t “hack the election.” What they “hacked” was the Democratic National Committee headquarters. And really, just one person’s email account. It’s good to remember that. So how did it happen? You haven’t heard of the “typo heard round the world.”? Charles Delevan worked for the Democratic National Convention. He was an IT guy. John Podesta was the chair of the DNC. He received a phishing email, purporting to be from Google. But it looked suspicious, so it was passed on to Delevan to inspect. Delevan claims to have seen it for what it was. He sent an email to Podesta saying: “this is a legitimate email.” He claims that what he meant to say is: “this is NOT a legitimate email.” Regardless, he advised Podesta to change his email password right away. So Podesta, seeing that it was “a legitimate email,” according to Delevan, used the link originally sent to him in the phishing email. Podesta’s email was hacked. The emails were passed on to WikiLeaks and posted for all the world to see. The rest is history. And what has resulted? Donald Trump was elected to the presidency. PizzaGate became a thing. The DNC was exposed as having rigged the campaign AGAINST Bernie Sanders in favor of Hillary Clinton, disillusioning Democrats who might have held their nose and voted for her. And more generally speaking, the undermining of faith in the media, in the party system, in US politics, in truth. And if you believe Trump is a terrible president, the waning of American prestige, influence, and leadership around the globe. This was one minuscule event that almost never gets covered. But then, what more is there to say? But all our national politics for the last two years has hinged on one unwritten word: NOT. It’s been a crazy couple years. Pour yourselves a bourbon over ice and take a read: I Talked to the IT Guy Whose “Typo” Helped Russia (Maybe) Hack the Election

The Most Expensive Hyphen in History. The typo that destroyed a Nasa Rocket  On July 22, 1962, at 9:20 PM, the Mariner I sat idly on its platform, ready to make history. After investing years of construction, calculation, and funding, NASA had high hopes that its rocket would successfully conduct a flyby survey of Venus, thus shifting the Space Race's momentum back to the home front. In every way, it was poised to set a space travel precedent. But when the rocket embarked, it was clear there'd be no cause for celebration: less than 5 minutes into flight, Mariner I exploded, setting back the U.S. government $80 million. The root cause for this disaster? A lone omitted hyphen, somewhere deep in hand-transcribed mathematical code. NASA delineates what went wrong in the moments following the launch: “The booster had performed satisfactorily until an unscheduled yaw-lift maneuver was detected by the range safety officer. Faulty application of the guidance commands made steering impossible and were directing the spacecraft towards a crash, possibly in the North Atlantic shipping lanes or in an inhabited area. [A range safety officer subsequently ordered its destructive abort.]” “[The hyphen] gives a cue for the spacecraft to ignore the data the computer feeds it until radar contact is once again restored. When that hyphen is left out, false information is fed into the spacecraft control systems. In this case, the computer fed the rocket in hard left, nose down and the vehicle obeyed and crashed.” In his 1968 book The Promise of Space, Arthur C. Clarke memorialized the typo as “the most expensive hyphen in history," a claim that is most likely true.

Not disastrous, it was the other way around. Did you know the name “Google” itself a typo? Shocking right! Origin of the name “Google”: In 1996, Larry Page and Sergey Brin called their initial search engine "BackRub," named for its analysis of the web's "back links." Larry's office was in room 360 of the Gates CS Building, which he shared with several other graduate students, including Sean Anderson, Tamara Munzner, and Lucas Pereira. In 1997, Larry and his officemates discussed a number of possible new names for the rapidly improving search technology. Sean recalls the final brainstorming session as occurring one day during September of that year. Sean and Larry were in their office, using the whiteboard, trying to think up a good name - something that related to the indexing of an immense amount of data. Sean verbally suggested the word "googolplex," and Larry responded verbally with the shortened form, "googol" (both words refer to specific large numbers). Sean was seated at his computer terminal, so he executed a search of the Internet domain name registry database to see if the newly suggested name was still available for registration and use. Sean is not an infallible speller, and he made the mistake of searching for the name spelled as “Google” which he found to be available.  Larry liked the name, and within hours he took the step of registering the name “Google” for himself and Sergey (the domain name registration record dates from September 15, 1997). Source:http://graphics.stanford.edu/~dk/google_name_origin.html

I have certainly seen some surprising non-consequences. Back in about 1980, when nobody had word processors or e-mail, and all documents went through the typing pool, our company had a reporting system called the “managers’ monthly letter”. Every manager in the company, down to the lowest department head, would present their “monthly letter” to their supervisor. As the letter went up the chain, only the most important elements in each junior manager’s monthly letter made it into the senior manager’s monthly letter, and so on all the way up to the Managing Director. It was a big company, with about 15,000 employees, and only the most critical of the company’s activities made it all the way up to the MD’s monthly letter. As it happened the project I was working on … let’s call it The Poseidon Project … was one of the most visible and potentially impactful in the company. In my report to my manager, I wrote that “reliability concerns in the Poseidon Project are now being urgently addressed”. This paragraph made it all the way to the MD, verbatim. I say verbatim, but that’s not actually correct. What made it to the MD’s monthly letter was “reliability concerns in the Poseidon Project are not being urgently addressed”. It says much about that company, and about the MD in question, that the MD never sought clarity on that issue. At least, not from anyone in my department!

A typo most likely cost Hillary Clinton the 2016 Presidential election. An aide to Hillary Clinton’s campaign chair, John Podesta, saw a warning email in his inbox back in March 2016, claiming to be from Google. Podesta needed to change his Gmail password immediately, the email said. That was actually a phishing e-mail from Russian hackers. Charles Delavan, a Clinton campaign aide, replied to another of Mr. Podesta’s aides, who had noticed the alert. “This is a legitimate e-mail, John needs to change his password immediately.” He meant to say “This is an illegitimate e-mail”, With another click, a decade of emails that Mr. Podesta maintained in his Gmail account — a total of about 60,000 — were unlocked for the Russian hackers. This gave Republicans the talking points, caused the Clinton campaign distractions, and allowed Russians to spread misinformation about Clinton which now we know probably cost her the election, thus making this probably the most consequential typo ever. For more information on this story, please click the link. How A Single Typo Led To The Unraveling Of Hillary Clinton's Campaign

I just now came across one typo that did not have disastrous consequences as far as we know. . . but it could have. Actually, I’m not sure if this should be called a typo per se, or just a mental slip; y’all can decide. In 2008, the TV chef, Anthony Worrall Thompson, gave an interview to Healthy and Organic Living magazine in which he meant to recommend a wild plant called “fat hen” (Chenopodium album). Fat hen is also known as “lamb’s quarters”, or bathua in Hindi. Leaves of fat hen can be eaten raw in salads, or cooked like spinach, and the seeds are also edible. Unfortunately, either he or the transcriber mixed up “fat hen” with “henbane”—which refers to Hyoscyamus niger, a very different wild plant. In small doses, Hyoscyamus niger causes drowsiness and eases pain. Increase the dose, and you’ll start hallucinating. Large enough doses will cause unconsciousness, seizures, and quite possibly a slight case of death. The magazine didn’t catch the error until after it had been printed and mailed out. The publisher issued a hasty retraction to its subscribers. Fortunately, as far as is known, no readers were poisoned by following the interview’s advice as printed. Check out: TV chef Worrall Thompson recommends deadly weed as salad ingredient.

Oh, yes. Many years ago, someone by the New York City Stock Exchange typed 11.000.000 million shares instead of 11.000.000 $ worth of shares. The worldwide trade almost collapsed. People were lucky that it had happened shortly before closing. Now, without a fixed time of ending the trade, a world-wide disaster would be the case. During the 1980s, a Soviet satellite missed a planet because of a single typo in half a million lines of code. And in 1973 I destroyed the entire programs of our university just by forgetting the right brackets in a formula. It took them 3 months to repair the damage. In the Ottoman Empire, they would write the character "M" in the names of Muslims and Christians differently. In the jail of Sinopi, there were two convicts with the same name beginning with M , one of them should be released, the other hanged. They hung the wrong guy.

response.answer_text: I write a weekly column about pub and beer related topics for my local paper. This offering from last year addresses the issue. The Bar Wife is a stickler for punctuation and spelling. No matter how many times I tell her that every time she corrects my grammar I love her a little bit fewer, she says ‘You are not funny’ and proceeds to put me right anyway. It has become a bit of a game that when we go out for a meal, we can’t eat anything that is spelt incorrectly on the menu. No mackeral or brockolli. If we have panini, it has to be at least two, and the rules did prevent me having a pint of cheap larger I saw advertised at a pub in Liverpool. Most of the time this is not too onerous, after all it is difficult to spell steak or pie incorrectly, but it could have become an issue in the Globe. Nothing wrong with the menu or the drinks, but later in the evening comes the time when one is ready for a trip out the back. There is no problem finding the toilets, but when you arrive it is labelled ‘Gentlemens’. Is it an attempt at a plural possessive which lacks an apostrophe or simply a mistake? Who knows? Needless to say, this was one occasion where the rules were ignored.Apostrophes are tricky things. When I write about breweries I am never sure whether the correct form is Adnams or Adnam’s, Elgoods or Elgood’s or Batemans/Bateman’s. I was in Nottingham recently when this very topic caused a heated debate. One of the great breweries in the city was Shipstones or Shipstone’s or even Shipstone. As it happened we were staying with Cathy, who has amassed a collection of Shipstone breweriana over the years and it was easy to look at the various advertising material, letter heads and old documents to come up with the definitive answer. Except there isn’t one. Over the years all three forms have appeared on various documents and objects, so we are none the wiser. Why does it matter? In a sense, it doesn’t unless you have the mind of an adolescent schoolboy. Shipstone is an anagram of ‘On the piss’, but it doesn’t work with the extra ‘s’.So, in the end, does it matter that much it we get a letter wrong or misplace an apostrophe? It may make a company look a bit foolish and unprofessional, but no real damage is done. Or is it? In 2007 the auction site eBay listed for sale an extremely rare bottle of ‘Allsops’ Arctic Ale, full and corked, with a wax seal’ This attracted two bids and sold for $304. A few weeks later the same bottle was re-advertised as ‘Museum quality ALLSOPPS’ ARCTIC ALE 1852 SEALED/FULL’. This listing attracted 157 bids and sold for over half a million dollars. Did you notice the difference? In the first listing, the vendor had missed a letter p from the name of the brewery and therefore most of the collectors did not pick up the sale using the site’s search engine.Was this the most expensive mistake ever? Nowhere near. Look up how the Pacific Bell Yellow Pages listed a travel agent as a specialist in erotic travel instead of exotic travel and had to pay $19 million as compensation for loss of bookings. Check out how Chile issued a 50 peso in 2008 coin with the countries name spelt as Chiie, or how copy mistakes in navigation tables lead to the loss of 4 battleships and 2000 men in the English Channel in 1707. Perhaps the Bar Wife has a point.

Yes, almost happened to a friend of mine once; on graduation day.  His name was Malik and he told me how they nearly messed his name up. Being bored waiting on them to call us up, I further inquired. He told me about another boy from our class, “Malic.” And, I remembered this boy. Malic was not graduating with us. Because, he was in Special Ed, and in my school they just “let” them play around rather then work. It was nothing they could do, they weren’t trained for this—no money to afford the right teachers. Anyways, Malik said they mixed him and Malic up on graduating class list. Now normally you wouldn’t be able to tell the difference, they’re both pronounced the same: Muh-leek. Their last name, however, is distinguishable. This would have led to embarrassment and probably shame.  Just imagine being ready to be called up, you’re in your assigned seat, thinking everything is going to go perfect. You get up and walk up to the stage. It’s finally happening! No more getting up at 6 for school, having teachers tell you what to do, no homework assignments, and most of all your taking a big step into adulthood. What you work for the last 12 years is finally about to be achieved; in front of your families and with your friends. But, they say the other kid name, leaving you stunned, not knowing wether to grab it or let them know their mistake. — That’ll be ruining a great day.

Well, not a typo and not disastrous consequences but something along those lines. In many countries is marketed a feminine hygiene product line under the name of Libresse So Slim. Also here in Denmark.  Which is all fine and dandy, except … "so slim" in Danish means sow slime. Literally. Without any ambiguity!! Rather unfortunate, i should say, considering the nature of the product.  It never ceases to amaze me that this company would allow itself to market a product towards female menstrual secretion with the headline of sow slime. Aiai caramba!! These guys are really, really ballsy. Or really, really stupid. Or just blatantly disrespectful towards the countries and languages where they market their stuff. Amazingly, this product has been sold to Danish women for decades and continues to do so, so I guess the women don't feel offended. Which btw is rather surprising considering the myriad of stuff in general which might offend women, in particular at the times when they do need to use this product :) Funnily, on several occasions I have pointed out these ads for my danish peers of both gender, and I have yet to experience anyone not saying "I don't see the problem". Only when I remind them of our danish language they suddenly are able to recognize the bizarreness of it all. Just goes to show I guess, that we see what we expect rather than what's really there.  So Slim | Libresse (danish)

I have been avid reader of history and specifically the history of Marathas and Peshwas who ruled a major part of this country at one point of time in history from Afghanistan to south India. However the history of Pashwa always carried this blot of infighting and rivalries within the family. The famous or rather historic typo was the one made by Anandi Bai the wife of Maratha General Raghunath Rao. After the death of the majority of the leading men of the family in the battle of Panipat in 1761, the surviving Peshwa also died with the guilt of the destruction brought about by the war. Narayan Rao, 16 year old boy was named as the heir and the next Peshwa (Ruler) to the throne. His uncle Raghunath Rao was named as his guide to help him with the administration. Anandi Bai, wife of Raghunath Rao was angered by this. Relations were spoilt and at one point of time Narayan Rao ordered the house arrest of his uncle Raghunath Rao. This angered Anandi Bai further and she convinced her husband to seek help from rivals of the Peshwa - the Gardi Tribe and asked him to write a letter to them seeking their help to enter the palace and free him from the Peshwa Narayan Rao. After Raghunath Rao wrote the letter and signed and sealed it, Anandi Bai secretly altered the letter. There was a line in the letter which read "Peshwa la Dhara" meaning "Capture the Peshwa" and she changed the word "Dhara" to "Mara" which read as "Peshwa la Mara" meaning "Kill the Peshwa". It was easier to do this in the Marathi language which was used to write this letter. As a result, in the night, the assassins entered the palace and killed all the guards, they then captured the young peshwa and killed him, it is said that when he was attacked, the young peshwa ran to his uncle in the palace and cried for help "uncle Please help me" but his uncle stood still till the assassins cut him to pieces and threw them in the river. It is said the ghost of Peshwa still haunts the palace and on full moon nights one can hear those cries " Uncle Save Me" ...That's an urban legend may be. Apart from this tragedy there were a few other typos like 1. The spelling of Chile was spelt wrongly on its own coins in 2008 and the currency went into circulation2. During the 17th Century, one English king assigned the task of recreating the bible and the printing press missed a word "NOT" in the line "Thou shalt commit adultery" I think later on he punished the printing press.

How about one that caused the destruction of a NASA rocket? This is Mariner 1:  On July 22,1962,the Mariner was built and software was written for it to fly close to Venus and conduct a survey. However, that wasn’t going to happen. The launch went fine,for a while. Less than 5 minutes later, however, the rocket went out of control and it instead got set on a crash course. The range safety officer then triggered the destruction of the rocket. The cost? 80 Million US dollars in 1962 money. According to an online inflation calculator, that’s around $665 million in today’s money. And it was all due to the fact that a dash (Or a hyphen, as some people call it) was missing from the code responsible for making the rocket functional. It was termed “The most expensive hyphen in history”.

A typo which almost had me lost my job… It was in my previous company. I generally never used to take any leaves. While one day, I took a day off and was spending my time home. I was on my computer and had my office account logged in on Skype, without realising I was online there… Our Director (Now the Vice President) for some emergency pinged me on Skype. Yes. There are a few infamous cases. In Dec., 2005, read what happened when a typo was made by Mizuho Securities Co. Perhaps Google this name, and “bank” and “typo,” and add “stock exchange,” to the search phrase. You should find many articles. This was a simple typo that cost them hundreds of millions of dollars, in only one day. As I recall, it was a finally a $340 million dollar typo. The actual typo: The typist intended to type that he wanted to sell one share of stock at 610,000 yen. (That is a bit over $5000.00 in U.S. money). The typist managed to enter a request to sell 610,000 shares of stock, at only 1 yen. In one day, the company could tell it had lost about $250 million in US dollars. By the time of the final calculations, it ended up costing the bank $340 million dollars total. The bank sued the stock exchange, for not allowing them to cancel once the typo had been entered. The suit was not successful. A $340,000,000.00 typo. The Typo Heard 'Round Tokyo Here is another fun one: See if you can find some news stories by using your search engine. Try: “Banner Travel Services.” This one was in 1988. They are closed now, but used to be in Sonoma California. They ordered an ad in their yellow pages. Their ad was to promote travel arrangements to exotic destinations. A typographical mistake during the production process substituted the “x” for an “r,” so that “exotic travel” became “erotic travel.” The travel agency lost 80% of its business. The Yellow Pages publisher offered to give them their money back for the ad — $230. The travel agency sued. It won. The Yellow Pages had to pay up, more than $19 million. Travel Agent Angry Over Phone Book Typo Finally, a fascinating political one: I also seem to recall that a sealed letter was sent by GHW Bush to Saddam Hussein, two days before the U.S. invaded Iraq (the first invasion, way back in 1991). This was the Gulf War — where GHW Bush had warned Saddam to withdraw all his troops from Kuwait, a January 16 deadline, or the U.S. would absolutely attack. The sealed letter of course had to be translated. But, in the final versions that were delivered to Hussein, to try to tell him how he could avoid an all-out war, one of the most important terms offered up was missing a comma. It was one of those: “X, and/or Y, or X and/or Z, or X and Z” -type of statements. It had several and/or statements. But, a comma was left off. Afterward, there were actual reports by those in the room that Saddam Hussein and his team would have done as asked, had it only been clear — but a missing comma made it sound as if Hussein had to do all three, no matter what. He actually, as I recall —needed to only comply with two of the “Demands.” That, as I recall, was received two days prior. Hussein refused, so on Jan. 16, 1991, the US began bombing, and attacked. Was it really an entire war, over a missing comma? This was reported on, in the legitimate press, several times, after the war was in full swing. Was it really an entire war, over a missing comma?

Well, in recent history, some typos have definitely been disastrous in monetary terms for many a institutions and governments. In brief, have a look below. In 1872, just a single misplaced comma cost the USA Government $2M. To put that in perspective, today that comma would be worth over $50M. The tiny error was made in the US Tariff Act, instead of making tropical 'fruit-plants' exempt from tariffs, the act used the wording 'fruit, plants' -- a rogue comma meant all tropical fruit and plants were free from charge. It took 2 years for the matter to get fixed. Just imagine the trauma the error guy must have gone through. In 2006, Alitalia Airlines accidentally listed business-class flights from Toronto to Cyprus at $39, instead of $3,900. 2000 quick-thinking travelers took advantage of the mistake, booking tickets as fast as they could. When the airline tried to cancel the tickets, they suffered a massive backlash from their customers. Ultimately they decided to cut their losses and keep the deal in place for those who'd bought it, but it cost the company somewhere in the region of $7.2M. On July 22, 1962 the Mariner 1 space probe exploded shortly after liftoff, in one of the most expensive typo related incidents in history. NASA investigators concluded that the omission of a single hyphen in the guidance software application had led to a series of false course correction signals. The rocket was then deliberately detonated to prevent the rocket crashing down in a populated area. Political pressure to get the rocket in space was blamed for the rushed preparations and the error’s reason. The rocket was around $80–$150M. Bollocks right? There have been many other incidents as well. I just quoted a few.

A family, in UK, called for an ambulance when their 18-month old kid went into a cardiac arrest. Upon follow up by the hospital, the dispatch rechecked the status of the ambulance and found out their horrible error. In 2005, Ellen Tauscher, a member of the House of Reps, made a reference to the detonation of the Storax Sedan thermonuclear earthmover by Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory in Nevada in 1962 as an example of a nuclear explosive test that resulted in significant fallout. “Sedan” was incorrectly transcribed as “Sudan” in Congressional Record. What a difference an ‘r’ makes. There was a Californian travel company called Banner Travel Services who in 1988 published an advert in the Pacific Bell Yellow Pages to advertise its services. The advert was supposed to promote the company's excellent travel arrangements to exotic destinations. However, a typing error in the production process substituted an ‘r’ for the ‘x’ and hence, the exotic travel destinations became the ‘erotic’ travel destinations. The Yellow Pages company offered to refund the original listing fee, of $230. But the principal of the travel company said her business had suffered a complete loss of reputation as well as 80% of its customer base. The little ‘r’ error went on to cost Yellow Pages more than $19 million when judgement was found against them. Most of us may have heard the saying it is always advisable to watch ‘our p’s and q’s’, but in this case I would keep a very close eye on the ‘r’s and x’s to be sure.

Not disastrous, but funny. Several decades ago, I was trying to get a letter hand-delivered to a customer very quickly. I had the draft approved. I gave it to our best secretary, who never ever made a mistake. I asked her to file the carbon copy (literally made with carbon paper), got the original signed by the appropriate authority at our company, and jumped into the car to visit the customer. The customer was quite pleased, but displayed a shock as he read the letter. “Is there anything wrong?”, I asked. Well this one got caught in time, not really disastrous, but funny. One evening my dad came home from work and he kept laughing. I asked him what was up. Dad worked for IBM and wrote announcement letters for the Data Processing Division. That day he was proofreading an announcement of a policy change. Back then IBM was really in the rental business. Most customers leased their mainframe computers, and were charged rent based on usage. Often this was based on a certain number of hours per day, in units of 8 hour shifts. If a lease called for say 2 shifts per day, the machine could be used for additional shifts for a fee. The title of the announcement dad was working on was Something like “Extra Shift Premium” The typo was the lack of one important letter in the penultimate word.

I once had a GM that used to work in banking. He had a friend who used to work in London in “high value transactions” at a bank. He told a story about how one Friday she was in a hurry to go on a trip to France for the weekend. So she rushed through the transactions she had left to verify and approve and went away. Monday morning she arrives at here office to find the CEO sitting in her chair. He looks her up and down and says “I’m awfully glad you decided to come in to work today” Apparently she was in such a rush that she had keyed in her own account number in one of the (over 10 million pound) transactions. There was the $2,000,000 comma. The $2-million comma A misplaced comma in a contract between Rogers Communication and Aliant cost Rogers $2,000,000. There is what the contract said: The agreement "shall continue in force for a period of five years from the date it is made, and thereafter for successive five year terms, unless and until terminated by one year prior notice in writing by either party." And what Rogers claimed the intent was: The agreement "shall continue in force for a period of five years from the date it is made, and thereafter for successive five year terms unless and until terminated by one year prior notice in writing by either party." The boldface emphasis is mine (not the contract). In the former, Aliant could cancel the contract on one year notice. In the latter, Aliant would have to give one year notice prior to a five year cycle (so essentially six years).

One hyphen costed 80 million dollars  There was a typo that caused a 80 million dollar NASA rocket to be scrapped. One of the NASA engineers was supposed to add a hyphen to a formula but he didn't and the rocket could not reach Venus. It was aborted an hour into flight because it would miss it's destination. Apparently that hyphen was supposed to tell the rocket some instructions but without the instructions it would not reach the desired location and would miss Venus.

The typo I shall choose is one I know from programming. I am not sure if it is apocryphal or not, but here goes. Apparently, the Mariner 1 probe, which was aimed at Venus in July 1962, went off course due to a typo in some FORTRAN code. I paraphrase here, but what should have been written as:   DO 20 I = 1, 5 C SOME LOOP CODE   20 CONTINUE was written as:   DO 20 I = 1. 5 C SOME LOOP CODE   20 CONTINUE Now, if you know FORTRAN you’ll know that spaces are not significant, and the first line in the second code sample is equivalent to the following assignment:   DO20I = 1.5 rather than the start of a loop specification as per the first code sample. So, for a “,” being written as a “.”, a probe was lost. Wowza! Thanks to Castillo Evans for the A2A.

This is from the website “Priceonomics” (The Typo that Destroyed a NASA Rocket): “On July 22, 1962, at 9:20 PM, the Mariner I sat idly on its platform, ready to make history. After investing years of construction, calculation, and funding, NASA had high hopes that its rocket would successfully conduct a flyby survey of Venus, thus shifting the Space Race’s momentum back to the home front. One day the monks decided in Chapter to put a Latin inscription above the monastery main gate that said Porta patens esto. Nulli claudator honesto Which means “the gate is to be open. It won't close for any honest person". Sadly enough, Martin wrote: Porta patens esto nulli. Claudatur honesto Which means: “the gate is to be open to nobody. It will close for the honest" And because of a full stop, Martin wasn't abbot anymore, and lost his cape.

We have a proverb in Italian that says: “Per un punto Martin perse la cappa”. It literally means “For a dot Martin lost his mantle” The tradition says that Martin was an abbot. The mantle was the symbol of his title. He had a latin inscription engraved on the entrance of his abbey. Only, a dot was placed at the wrong place. Instead of reading something like “The door is open. It shall not be closed to any honest man”, the wrongly placed dot changed the meaning into “The door is closed to anybody. It shall be closed to the honest man”. When the church hyerarchy was made aware of the engraving, poor Martin was stripped of his title of abbot (lost his mantle).

Space probe Mariner 1 got lost in 1962 because a computer program had a full stop instead of a comma. In FORTRAN, spaces are optional, even in variable names, so what should have beenDO 15 I = 1, 100 [loop 100 times]wasDO 15 I = 1. 100 [assign 1.100 to variable DO15I] So code that should have been iteratively calculated 100 times, getting more accurate each time, just got run once, like going in the general direction of a vague arm-wave. Mariner 1 / FORTRAN Bug
